The White House Office of the First Lady has announced the "Smithsonian Salutes Ray Charles: In Performance At The White House" event, which will take place on Wednesday, February 24th. The event will include an evening performance and a daytime student workshop, both honoring the music of Ray Charles. The President and First Lady will invite top contemporary artists to perform, including Yolanda Adams, Leon Bridges, Andra Day, Anthony Hamilton, Brittany Howard, Demi Lovato, Sam Moore, Jussie Smollett, The Band Perry, and Usher. The President's remarks will be pooled press and the entire event will be streamed live on WhiteHouse.gov. The program will be broadcast on PBS stations nationwide on February 26th and will also be simulcast on cable channel TV One. This event is the sixteenth in the "In Performance at the White House" series during President Barack Obama's administration, which has previously honored artists such as Stevie Wonder, Sir Paul McCartney, Burt Bacharach, Hal David, Carole King, and more. In addition to the evening performance, the First Lady will host a daytime workshop for students, where participating students will learn about Ray Charles' life, musical legacy, and his influence on today's musicians. Featured performers from the evening event will share their experiences and answer student questions about the music and entertainment world. Students from 10 schools and community organizations across the country will be participating in the workshop.